00:00:02.070 --> 00:00:14.459
&gt;&gt;Nidia: Good afternoon everyone. Welcome
to another Authors@Google talk. I am happy

00:00:14.459 --> 00:00:27.000
to introduce Les McKeown, author of 'Predictable
Success'. Les McKeown has launched and managed

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.029
over 40 businesses and is the co-founder of
an incubation company that helped hundreds

00:00:29.029 --> 00:00:30.769
of entrepreneurs launch businesses, employing
thousands worldwide. This book hit the market

00:00:30.769 --> 00:00:33.390
with a splash and is said to be an incredibly
useful blueprint for any leader who is looking

00:00:33.390 --> 00:00:35.559
for sustainable growth. As per tradition,
we will have book signing and a 15 minute

00:00:35.559 --> 00:00:38.320
Q &amp; A at the end. We're just waiting for a
book thing to set up. So, with that said,

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:39.320
let's welcome Les.
[applause]

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:53.590
&gt;&gt;Les McKeown: Thank you very much, Nidia.
I appreciate it. And thank you for, all of

00:00:53.590 --> 00:00:59.399
you for giving some time to be here. I appreciate
it. I want to thank the various folks who

00:00:59.399 --> 00:01:08.000
helped me get here. Not the least, Jenny Blake
in her absence, Nidia Landria, and Alyssa.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:17.640
I actually lived for a number of years from
1997 to about 2006 in Marin. So it's a little

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:24.430
bit frightening to realize that when I first
moved here, none of this existed. And now

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:33.600
I, well, it all exists. It's pretty bewilderin'.
I don't come from these parts as you might

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:42.800
gather from my accent. I'm from Texas. [laughter]
[laughs] I'm from Belfast in Ireland. Belfast

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:48.790
is the part of Ireland that you come from.
You go to Dublin, right? And you come from

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:54.140
Belfast and I've come from Belfast. But I
moved out in 1997 like I said and my accent

00:01:54.140 --> 00:01:59.340
has decided not to relocate. So I'm just talkin'
for a little bit for you to get accustomed

00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:07.649
to the cadences of my voice. The word that
you'll have most difficulty with is 'it'.

00:02:07.649 --> 00:02:15.940
'It' is a number between seven and nine. [laughter]
But it's also part of a lot of words 'demonstrit',

00:02:15.940 --> 00:02:20.900
'ingrati-it'. So if something isn't gelling,
it's because there's an 'it' in there somewhere

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:25.300
or other.
What I want to share with you today as Niddi

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:33.660
mentioned is essentially what's in my book
but I'm gonna prove that nobody needs to read

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:39.910
a book if you've got 45 minutes and the guy
who wrote it in the same room. [laughs] [laughter]

00:02:39.910 --> 00:02:45.080
A lot of nodding going on. Because [clears
throat] I believe that I'm gonna be able to

00:02:45.080 --> 00:02:51.910
communicate to you pretty comprehensively
more or less all that I've covered in there

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:58.570
because of the fact that it's pretty much
instantly intuitive. I doubt very much if

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:03.450
I'm gonna share with you anything this afternoon
that any of you are gonna think, 'Oh my goodness.

00:03:03.450 --> 00:03:08.150
I never knew any of that.' What's gonna happen
is I'm gonna share with you a bunch of stuff

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:15.950
that you 'll recognize but almost certainly
you hadn't put a name to beforehand. And in

00:03:15.950 --> 00:03:20.850
order to do that, I want to share with you
first of all a little bit of background about

00:03:20.850 --> 00:03:26.260
myself. Not just because I like talking about
myself. But because I think it's important

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:32.870
for you to understand where what I am about
to show you came from. Because given that

00:03:32.870 --> 00:03:37.600
I'm aware of the environment in which you
operate every day, what I'm about to say might

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:42.820
mean that all of you might leave the room
immediately at least mentally if not physically.

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:49.560
There isn't a single thing I'm about to show
you that is subject to objective proof. I'm

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:57.870
gonna show you what I have learned subjectively
over about 36 years or so doing what I do.

00:03:57.870 --> 00:04:02.970
That doesn't mean that it doesn't have validity
obviously. But what it does mean is that you

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:06.900
need to know the context from which it came
from in order to ascribe whatever validity

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:12.600
you might put to it.
I qualified in the UK originally. This is

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:16.699
something I tried to keep a secret but unfortunately
the people that published the book actually

00:04:16.699 --> 00:04:20.630
slapped it on the box. So I've had to start
to 'fess up to it again. I'm actually a CPA

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:25.320
by training or a chartered accountant which
is the somewhat posh name we give ourselves

00:04:25.320 --> 00:04:33.570
back in the UK. A CPS. And I qualified as
a CPA not because I had any interest in CPA-ing

00:04:33.570 --> 00:04:39.200
in terms of doing the legacy work of accounts
and tax and so forth. It was because I had

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:49.100
a freakishly developed interest in business
as a kid. I, I, I can't explain it. It's just

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:54.970
something weird that happened in my DNA at
some point. And I wanted to understand how

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:58.460
businesses worked. And somebody gave me a
really good piece of advice which was, 'If

00:04:58.460 --> 00:05:03.120
you understand the numbers, then 90% of everything
else will flow from there.' Now I'm gonna

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:08.850
show you in a moment or two why that's not
true but it was a good starting point. By

00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:14.370
the way, I hope you'll forgive me. I'm not
going to do any Power Point. Is that okay

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:19.260
with you? [audience chuckles] I'm not gonna
switch the lights off and flick at anything.

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:24.930
I'm, I'm beta testing a brand new technology.
I have downloaded everything I know about

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:30.830
the topic into these four small output devices
[audience chuckles] and I'm amazingly able

00:05:30.830 --> 00:05:35.870
to access randomly whatever part of whatever
I want to share with you at any point and

00:05:35.870 --> 00:05:41.560
it'll appear here as opposed to doing some
linear display up on the screen. And what

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:48.890
I'll show you in a moment or two began to
evolve as the result of the work I did when

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:55.110
I was in practice. What I started to do pretty
early on was to advise people on launching

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:59.860
businesses which was a ridiculous thing to
do because I didn't know anything about launching

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:06.050
businesses. But I happened to be working in
Northern Ireland at a time when there was

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:12.090
a, a very strong interest in launching indigenous
local businesses, largely because there was

00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:16.560
such a high unemployment rate. There were
very few other options for other people. And

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:22.270
I was fascinated by this. So a number of people
were brave enough, dumb enough, something

00:06:22.270 --> 00:06:29.991
enough to allow me to take my financial understanding
and try to help them build a business that

00:06:29.991 --> 00:06:37.270
would succeed. Now of course you could pretty
quickly be able to work out what as an accountant,

00:06:37.270 --> 00:06:42.270
I was brainwashed, sorry trained, to understand
was the most important thing in a business.

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:45.401
What do you reckon that might be?
&gt;&gt;male #1: Money.

00:06:45.401 --> 00:06:49.350
&gt;&gt;Les McKeown: Money, cash, profits. The numbers,
the green, the dollar. All that sort of stuff.

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:53.460
Let's call it the finance. If the finance
was right, everything else would follow. And

00:06:53.460 --> 00:07:00.020
so I worked very, very hard at trying to help
people understand that if we could get their

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:04.130
cash flow right, their balance sheet right,
their P and L account right, everything else

00:07:04.130 --> 00:07:11.790
would follow. And that worked pretty well.
I got to be very good at what I do. I got

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:16.030
first place in the accounting exams that I
took. And to this day, just lookin' around

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:20.010
the room, there may not be enough of you who
are old enough to remember this. But you may

00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:23.670
recall a couple of years ago, these printed
books came out. I think they were sort of

00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:28.600
laser printed with dots and if you twisted
them a certain way in a strange light and

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:33.340
did weird things with your eyes, a dolphin
would leap out at you. Or a building would

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:38.700
appear. These 3-D representations. Well that's
sort of what happens when I look at a set

00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:44.450
of financial statements. I can see the business.
It, it, it becomes a three dimensional thing.

00:07:44.450 --> 00:07:50.680
And that comes out of all of that work I did
helping launch businesses. Now to fast forward

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:56.610
real quick by the time I was 35, I had on
my account or with other people launched 42

00:07:56.610 --> 00:08:00.770
businesses.
Nothing spectacular; a specialist publishing

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:06.000
company, a tool and die manufacturing company,
probably an entire industry that barely exists

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.639
these days. Excuse me. I owned, I bought and
operated the Master License for Pizza Hut

00:08:12.639 --> 00:08:18.919
in Ireland which was great fun trying to sell
flat Italian breads to Irish people. [audience

00:08:18.919 --> 00:08:23.850
chuckles] We had no destination restaurants
then. There was no, there was no McDonald's.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:27.620
There was no Wendy's. There was no Burger
King. There was nothing. We were the first

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:33.690
thing that was a destination branded restaurant.
And to this day you can still go to the first

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:36.310
Pizza Hut that I opened in a little town called
Carryduff.

00:08:36.310 --> 00:08:41.430
And it's the only Pizza Hut in the world so
far as I am aware that is allowed to manufacture

00:08:41.430 --> 00:08:45.839
and sell fries. The only way we could get
our compatriots to buy pizza was if they could

00:08:45.839 --> 00:08:50.880
get potato in some form along with it. And
in fact, many people at the start when we

00:08:50.880 --> 00:08:55.400
tried to spin the concept of choosing toppings,
wanted to know if chips as we call it was

00:08:55.400 --> 00:09:03.339
one of the toppings. So I had a lot of fun
with that and, but even as a dumb Irish guy

00:09:03.339 --> 00:09:10.720
which is my solid qualification, after you've
done something 40 something times with two

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:16.589
really painful failures, you begin to see
some patterns, okay? And one of the patterns

00:09:16.589 --> 00:09:21.990
that I saw, in fact the most prominent pattern
that I saw was that a successful business

00:09:21.990 --> 00:09:28.740
wasn't just about the numbers. It was about
the numbers, sure. It didn't, it did no harm

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:35.640
to get the business well financed, right?
But it was at least equally important that

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.790
you got the right people. In other words,
you could throw as much money as you wanted

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:48.020
at the wrong team and a bunch of idiots can
keep spending your money, right? And the first,

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:52.420
stripping out the reference, the totally unnecessary
reference to idiots, we could go back to the

00:09:52.420 --> 00:09:57.740
first dot com boom and see that that happened
a lot. A lot of money was thrown at businesses

00:09:57.740 --> 00:10:03.800
that spent it, went up in flames. There might
have been a perfectly good business idea underneath

00:10:03.800 --> 00:10:09.290
that or not. You wouldn't know. On the other
hand, really good groups of people I discovered

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:14.500
could launch highly successful businesses
with very little money. We call it 'bootstrapping''

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:20.430
these days. But ideally you'd want them both
to be the same. You'd want good finance, good

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:29.180
team. That seemed to me to be the best combination.
So at that time when I was about 36, 37, the

00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:34.540
UK government, which was then much more interventionist
in business, came along and asked me and one

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:40.560
other guy if we would start teaching other
people how to launch businesses. Essentially

00:10:40.560 --> 00:10:47.010
what, if you know of them at all, organizations
like Techstar or Y Combinator are doing except

00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:52.260
we didn't have a tech only focus. We were
focused on anything that would launch a reasonable

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:58.149
business. And the reason was simple. The UK
at that point was a branch economy of the

00:10:58.149 --> 00:11:05.490
U.S. by and large and South Korea. We had
GM, Ford, Hyundai, Daewoo, LG, Lucky Gold

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:11.310
Star. All big employers in those days. But
if Ford took a cold that shut down a plant

00:11:11.310 --> 00:11:15.660
in Liverpool, then 20,000 people would be
out of work. So what the UK government did

00:11:15.660 --> 00:11:21.170
was ask myself and this one other guy who
was also a serial entrepreneur would we help

00:11:21.170 --> 00:11:25.840
other people launch businesses.
Fast forward another 10 years with 120 people

00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:31.880
in a consulting group worldwide. We've launched
about 3,000 businesses off the runway. We're

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:37.940
doing this in, in 13 offices around the world.
And we're just watching these businesses take

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:43.100
off like fighter planes off a ,whatever that
ship thing is,I'm trying to imagine with this

00:11:43.100 --> 00:11:46.720
gesture with my hand what's the name of the
ship that has fighter planes on it.

00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:48.529
&gt;&gt;male #2: Aircraft carrier.
&gt;&gt;Les McKeown: Aircraft carrier. That's it.

00:11:48.529 --> 00:11:53.580
Okay.
Tortured metaphors -- not good. So [clears

00:11:53.580 --> 00:12:00.090
throat] here's the weird thing. About two
to three years into this phase, this incubation

00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:05.260
phase where we're helping people launch businesses,
what do you think might start to happen to

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:08.010
some of those businesses?
&gt;&gt;Audience Member: [inaudible]

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:15.140
&gt;&gt;Les McKeown: Some of them started to tank.
Correct. And this was not a pleasant experience

00:12:15.140 --> 00:12:21.710
for us and certainly it wasn't a pleasant
experience for them. In fact, our remuneration,

00:12:21.710 --> 00:12:26.720
the way we got paid, was largely focused on
job creation numbers. That's the reason why

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:33.101
the government agencies were paying us to
help start these private businesses. And every

00:12:33.101 --> 00:12:38.230
time one of them closed, that was a net job
loss and they were trying to do a thing that

00:12:38.230 --> 00:12:43.320
I had to struggle very hard to get my head
around. They were trying to do a thing called

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:49.110
'taking money back' which is not an idea that
an Irish person really carries around much

00:12:49.110 --> 00:12:54.490
in their head. Every pine is a prisoner back
there. But we started to get call backs on

00:12:54.490 --> 00:13:00.190
what we were being paid. It was also, both
intellectually and professionally incredibly

00:13:00.190 --> 00:13:05.930
disheartening. Because we were working on
this twin track of having well financed businesses

00:13:05.930 --> 00:13:10.540
with really good teams. We were doing a lot
of hard work to put good quality teams together.

00:13:10.540 --> 00:13:17.910
[clears throat] And so I got personally obsessed
with trying to understand why these businesses,

00:13:17.910 --> 00:13:22.370
two to three years down the line, despite
fitting our template, were still failing.

00:13:22.370 --> 00:13:26.540
And this was setting aside those businesses
that had a perfectly understandable reason

00:13:26.540 --> 00:13:30.900
to fail ;like the market got away from them
or technology changed immediately or they

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:36.240
had an economic headwind or whatever. These
were good businesses run by good business

00:13:36.240 --> 00:13:41.089
people, well financed and yet still a high
percentage of them,well, it wasn't a high

00:13:41.089 --> 00:13:44.970
percentage but it was a high enough percentage
were starting to fail to bother me. It was

00:13:44.970 --> 00:13:49.880
at that point that I moved over to the US.
I sold my share in the, in the business. I

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:56.050
wanted to focus on nothing but trying to understand
why second stage growth was such a problem

00:13:56.050 --> 00:13:59.920
for these businesses. And we'd been doing
work, we had offices here in San Francisco

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:04.690
and in Toronto and in Boston. I came over
here, took that work over, got a much bigger

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:11.380
area to play with and began to look at solely
trying to understand why this was happening.

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:16.980
And pretty much,not right away, but six to
nine months at trying to work at this, it

00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:22.170
became obvious to me intuitively that there
could only be one other variable. If we had

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:27.269
the money right and we had good teams, the
only thing that could have changed was the

00:14:27.269 --> 00:14:31.620
structure, the environment within which those
teams were operating, and within which the

00:14:31.620 --> 00:14:37.260
funding was operating too. That something
must be shifting within the structure of the

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:43.110
business. It also seemed to me likely that
although I was looking at this because I'd

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:50.560
bumped my nose against this one specific point
of change, call it 'second stage growth',

00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:56.209
whatever you want. It seemed to me highly
likely there were other flex points or pivot

00:14:56.209 --> 00:15:01.920
points, call it what you want. And I devoted
really all of the time from '97 through to

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:07.240
about 2003 trying to get a handle on what
they were. I had this huge database of all

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:10.510
the businesses that I'd worked with before
and helped launch and I had a lot of people

00:15:10.510 --> 00:15:19.339
out here who helped me, at their time and
expense and energy, work at this. And also

00:15:19.339 --> 00:15:22.529
a lot of good people who had done a lot of
good research and work on it beforehand. And

00:15:22.529 --> 00:15:27.950
anyway, here's what I discovered over time.
Now what I'm gonna show you, I'm gonna talk

00:15:27.950 --> 00:15:34.870
about it and explain it in the context of
business and in the context of an organization

00:15:34.870 --> 00:15:40.120
overall. But what I discovered going through
is what I'm about to show you applies to any

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:45.990
group of two or more people who are trying
to achieve common goals. I have shared this

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:51.430
with marriage guidance counselors, two or
more people trying to achieve common goals.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:56.399
I've shared it with non-profits, with NGOs,
with divisions, departments, groups, teams,

00:15:56.399 --> 00:16:04.860
soccer leagues, mom and kids, yoga groups,
and Fortune 100 businesses, and mom and pop

00:16:04.860 --> 00:16:09.310
businesses. Any group of two or more people
trying to achieve common goals goes through

00:16:09.310 --> 00:16:14.149
the same seven stages and let me share them
with you.

